<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-oo-tradeoffs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Trade-offs</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        You now know about the three main OOP toolkits available in R. Now that
        you understand their basic operation and the principles that underlie
        them, we can start to compare and contrast the systems in order to
        understand their strengths and weaknesses.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-s4-vs-s3">
      <title>S4 versus S3</title>

      <p>
        S4 is a rigorous system that requires careful upfront design. It's
        well-suited for building up big systems (with multiple programmers)
        that evolve over time. S4 has one major advantage over S3: multiple
        dispatch. With S4 you can define a method that specialises on both
        the <c>x</c> and <c>y</c> argument:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
setGeneric("plus", function(x, y) standardGeneric("plus"))
setMethod("plus", signature("numeric", "numeric"), function(x, y) x + y)
        </input>
      </program>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="sec-r6-vs-s3">
      <title>R6 versus S3</title>

      <p>
        The primary difference between R6 and S3 is that R6 uses
        <em>encapsulated</em> OOP which includes mutable objects (with
        reference semantics). This helps solve a common dilemma you'll
        encounter in R: how do you create an object that represents a
        connection to an external resource (a database, or a file)?
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
